              <h3><a name="rinside_0.2.18"><b>RInside 0.2.18 on CRAN: Maintenance</b></a></h3>

	       
<p>A new release 0.2.18 of <a
href="https://dirk.eddelbuettel.com/code/rinside.html">RInside</a>
arrived on <a href="https://cran.r-project.org">CRAN</a> and in <a
href="https://www.debian.org">Debian</a> today. This is the first
release in ten months since the 0.2.17 release. <a
href="https://dirk.eddelbuettel.com/code/rinside.html">RInside</a>
provides a set of convenience classes which facilitate embedding of <a
href="https://www.r-project.org">R</a> inside of C++ applications and
programs, using the classes and functions provided by <a
href="https://www.rcpp.org">Rcpp</a>.</p>
<p>This release brings a contributed change to how the internal REPL is
called: <a href="https://github.com/djsamperi">Dominick</a> found the
current form more reliable when embedding R on Windows. We also updated
a few other things around the package.</p>
<p>The list of changes since the last release:</p>
<blockquote>
<h4 id="changes-in-rinside-version-0.2.18-2023-02-01">Changes in RInside
version 0.2.18 (2023-02-01)</h4>
<ul>
<li><p>The random number initialization was updated as in R.</p></li>
<li><p>The main REPL is now running via 'run_Rmainloop()'.</p></li>
<li><p>Small routine update to package and continuous
integration.</p></li>
</ul>
</blockquote>
<p>My <a
href="https://dirk.eddelbuettel.com/cranberries/">CRANberries</a> also
provides a short report with <a
href="http://dirk.eddelbuettel.com/cranberries/2023/02/01#RInside_0.2.18">changes
from the previous release</a>. More information is on the <a
href="https://dirk.eddelbuettel.com/code/rinside.html">RInside page</a>.
Questions, comments etc should go to the <a
href="https://lists.r-forge.r-project.org/cgi-bin/mailman/listinfo/rcpp-devel">rcpp-devel
mailing list</a> off the <a
href="https://r-forge.r-project.org/projects/rcpp/">Rcpp R-Forge
page</a>, or to issues tickets at the <a
href="https://github.com/eddelbuettel/rinside">GitHub repo</a>.</p>
<p>If you like this or other open-source work I do, you can now <a
href="https://github.com/sponsors/eddelbuettel">sponsor me at
GitHub</a>.</p>
<p style="font-size:80%; font-style:italic;">
This post by <a href="https://dirk.eddelbuettel.com">Dirk
Eddelbuettel</a> originated on his <a
href="https://dirk.eddelbuettel.com/blog/">Thinking inside the box</a>
blog. Please report excessive re-aggregation in third-party for-profit
settings.
